issues.title: typemapper: DateIntToShortMapper does not confine to specification
issues.body:
DateIntToShortMapper contains the following Java docs:

```
/**
 * Specialized Type Mapper that stores dates on the form {@code YYYYMMDD} as
 * a single {@code short} value (the number of days since the beginning of epoch
 * time).
 *
 * @author Emil Forslund
 * @since  3.0.11
 */
```

It specifies that the DateInt is mapped to a short value which is equal to the number of days since the beginning of epoch time. This does not hold. For example, the value 0 is mapped to 19700000 which is not a valid date, and parsing the IntDate 19700101 (first epoch day) gives the short 33 rather than the expected 0.

Selective INSERT does not return DEFALUTed field values
issues.body:
When persisting an entity, Speedment will return a possibly updated entity. Using selective persistence, the user may select to omit some fields from the operation and let the database fill them in. The returned entity will then have the omitted fields set to the values now present in the database. See https://speedment.github.io/speedment-doc/crud.html#selecting-fields-to-persist

This works for example for an autoincrementing ID field where persisting the entity with the ID field omitted will return an entity with the ID set to the generated value in the database.

It does _not_ work for DEFAULT values in the database, however. For those values, the field will not be updated. JDBC does not seem to return any values at the time of persistence here, but the default values are available via JDBC metadata.

Solving this problem would allow for more efficient Hazelcast persistence. The easiest solution is probably just to document this bevaviour.

issues.body:
Hi speedment team. I'm getting empty result when executing this code:
```java
List<InstallmentPurchasePayment> result = orm.getOrThrow(JoinComponent.class)
    .from(InstallmentPurchaseManager.IDENTIFIER)
    .where(InstallmentPurchase.BUYER_ID.equal(userId))
    .innerJoinOn(InstallmentPurchasePayment.INSTALLMENT_PURCHASE_ID)
    .equal(InstallmentPurchase.ID)
    .build(Tuples::of)
    .stream()
    .map(Tuple2::get1)
    .collect(Collectors.toList());
```

But when using ordinary filter method:
```java
List<InstallmentPurchasePayment> result = orm.getOrThrow(JoinComponent.class)
    .from(InstallmentPurchaseManager.IDENTIFIER)
    .innerJoinOn(InstallmentPurchasePayment.INSTALLMENT_PURCHASE_ID)
    .equal(InstallmentPurchase.ID)
    .build(Tuples::of)
    .stream()
    .filter(e -> e.get0().getBuyerId().equals(userId))
    .map(Tuple2::get1)
    .collect(Collectors.toList());
```

The result will be normal. This only happen when comparing UUID field with another UUID object in where clause (in this case BUYER_ID and userId). Other data type producing normal result. Thanks

issues.title: Compute: ComposedExpression trait is lost when performing operations on it
issues.body:
If you have a `ComposedExpression` and you perform an operation on it, you will perform it on the entire operation and not just the same step. That means that the resulting expression will not implement `ComposedExpression`.

**Example:**
```java
ToDouble<Person> getSalary = ...;
Function<Car, Person> getOwner = ...;

ToDouble<Car> ownerSalary = getSalary.compose(getOwner); // Implements ComposedExpression
ToDouble<Car> ownerSalarySqrt = getSalary.sqrt().compose(getOwner); // Implements ComposedExpression
ToDouble<Car> ownerSalarySqrt2 = getSalary.compose(getOwner).sqrt(); // Does NOT implement ComposedExpression
```

Since many internal operations rely on expressions being casted to for an example `ToDouble`, it means that those will loose any information known about the original expression, and can therefore not be properly analyzed.

A solution to this would be to let `ComposedExpression`-implementations apply any operations on the *inner* expression. That would simulate the first example where the operation is performed before the expressions are composed.

commitsDetails.commitMessage: runtime-compute: Fix #653 make ComposedExpression impls apply operations on the inner expression

issues.title: When mapping non-nullable time to long or int, wrapper is used instead of primitive value
issues.body:
If you have a non-nullable database type of `Time`, `Date` or `Timestamp` and you apply a TypeMapper to it to get an `int` or a `long`, Speedment will generate a `ComparableField<ENTITY, D, Integer>` instead of an `IntField<ENTITY, D>`. To keep backwards compatibility, we could fix this by adding new type mappers that always return a primitive type.

Suggested new TypeMappers:
* `DateToPrimitiveIntMapper`
* `DateToPrimitiveLongMapper`
* `TimestampToPrimitiveIntMapper`
* `TimestampToPrimitiveLongMapper`
* `TimeToPrimitiveIntMapper`
* `TimeToPrimitiveLongMapper`

issues.title: Wrong field declaration for autogenerated Enum fields
issues.body:
After generating the classes from the tool, the fields that are mapped to a enum doesn't get generated properly.

The `EnumField.create` method has a different signature that most of the other fields, this makes the generated code to be wrong:

```java
    /**
     * This Field corresponds to the {@link AccountsMessages} field that can be
     * obtained using the {@link AccountsMessages#getToStatus()} method.
     */
    EnumField<AccountsMessages, Byte, MessageStatus> TO_STATUS = EnumField.create(
            Identifier.TO_STATUS,
            AccountsMessages::getToStatus,
            AccountsMessages::setToStatus,
            new MessageStatusMapper(),
            false
    );
```

The correct one would be:

```java
    /**
     * This Field corresponds to the {@link AccountsMessages} field that can be
     * obtained using the {@link AccountsMessages#getToStatus()} method.
     */
    EnumField<AccountsMessages, Byte, MessageStatus> TO_STATUS = EnumField.create(
            Identifier.TO_STATUS,
            AccountsMessages::getToStatus,
            AccountsMessages::setToStatus,
            new MessageStatusMapper(),
            MessageStatus::name,
            MessageStatus::valueOf,
            MessageStatus.class
    );
```

issues.title: Rework the AutoClose stream property
issues.body:
Streams from databases are closed implicitly by the terminating operation to release database resources whereas normal Java collection streams are not closed implicitly creating a dissonant behavior with standard Streams which are not auto-closed

One idea would be to have the database streams call another method than close() to releases its database resources like ResultSet and Connection. Let's call it dbClose() for the sake of argument. So, instead of letting the terminating operation call close() it calls dbClose() instead.

-- Current Problem --

---Speedment Open source---
```
users.stream().onClose(()-> System.out.println("I was closed)).count();
```
will produce the output "I was closed"

---Java Collections---
```
List<User> userList = ...
userList.stream().onClose(()-> System.out.println("I was closed)).count();
```
will not produce any output

In the proposed solution above, none of the steams would produce an output.

issues.title: Collations are not used in ORDER BY rendering
issues.body:
Consider the following stream:
```
films.stream()
    .filter(FILM.RATING.equal(”PG-13”))
    .sorted(Film.TITLE.comparator())
```
Which will render to the following MySQL SQL statement:
```
 SELECT 
    `film_id`,`title`,`description`,`release_year`,
    `language_id`,`original_language_id`,`rental_duration`,`rental_rate`,
    `length`,`replacement_cost`,`rating`,`special_features`,
    `last_update` 
FROM 
    `sakila`.`film` 
WHERE
     (`sakila`.`film`.`rating`  = ? COLLATE utf8_bin) 
ORDER BY `sakila`.`film`.`title` ASC
```
This will produce a stream that is not ordered correctly since it does not ensure that the correct collation is used. So a film with the title "Alien" would be close to a film with the title "alien". The last part should instead be rendered to:

`ORDER BY `sakila`.`film`.`title` ASC  COLLATE utf8_bin;`

We should also introduce ignore case comparators like  `Film.TITLE.comparatorIgnoreCase()` to enable sorting in willful ignore case order.

issues.title: Optimizers cannot optimize columns with certain TypeMapper:s
issues.body:
If a column has a TypeMapper that does not preserve the order between the original database type and the Java type, then an Optimizer cannot render the column to an ORDER BY operation directly. 

The same problem will occur for certain filters (e.g. .greaterThen()) where the order is not retained over the TypeMapper. So these particular operations cannot be rendered to a WHERE statement.

There must be a way for an Optimizer to know if a TypeMapper preserves order.

It could be possible to describe a SQL mapping to apply, so that the order could be retained. However, it is difficult in the general case.

issues.title: How to deal with crowded tables (a.k.a actual tables on production systems)
issues.body:
This touches #400 #389 #413.

As far as I understand it there is currently no support in Speedment for:
* LIMITing the result set size by the dbms. It is always done in-memory by the JVM. 
* WHERE clauses containing OR linked expressions. They will also always be done in-memory.
* skipping (OFFSET) rows via SQL when using the workaround for OR queries described here: https://speedment.github.io/speedment-doc/predicate.html#or 

Now I've got an actual table currently containing 672807 rows. And I want to offer paging for its data grid on some frontend. I also want to offer a simple search capability where one entered term targets two OR linked fields in the table. I'm sure this has been done before.

With the current state of affairs in Speedment trying to implement this will:

1. when no search term was given:
* always fetch the whole table into JVM memory, then skip, then limit

2. when any search term was given:
* execute two queries, one for each term, then fully fetch both results
* compose both result sets using technique described here: https://speedment.github.io/speedment-doc/predicate.html#or
* again on the JVM side skip, then limit.

This is so utterly inefficient and slow that I cannot imagine I'm using Speedment (3.0.6) correctly. But OTOH I take my guidelines from here: https://speedment.github.io/speedment-doc

Some examples:

```
dataManager.stream()
  .sorted(...)                                     << performed by DBMS via SQL
  .skip(10L)                                     << performed by DBMS via SQL
  .limit(10L)                                     << performed by Java 
  .collect(Collectors.toList())
```
Runtimes
Plain SQL: 34ms
Speedment: ~6s


```
dataManager.stream()
  .filter(predicate1.or(predicate2))  << performed in-memory by Java
  .skip(10L)                                      << performed in-memory by Java
  .limit(10L)                                     << performed in-memory by Java 
  .collect(Collectors.toList())
```
Runtimes
Plain SQL: 34ms
Speedment: ~8s


```
StreamComposition.concatAndAutoClose(
  dataManager.stream().filter(predicate1),   << fully fetched, probably never reaches heap though
  dataManager.stream().filter(predicate2)    << fully fetched, probably never reaches heap though
)
.distinct()                                      << performed in-memory by Java 
.skip(offset)                                  << performed in-memory by Java 
.limit(pageSize)                            << performed in-memory by Java 
.collect(Collectors.toList());
```
Runtimes
Plain SQL: 34ms
Speedment: ~8s


We're not using Speedment in production yet. But if this turns out to be true I don't think we can.

issues.title: ApplicationBuilder, with-configs should use identifier
issues.body:
The `with`-methods in `ApplicationBuilder` allows you to configure part of the config tree during initialization, but the specified names are not completely logical since you need to include the project name even if it is impossible to configure multiple projects at the same time. We should change this to use the `Identifier`-syntax instead.

**Current**
```java
HaresApplication app = new HaresApplicationBuilder()
    .with(Table.class, "hares.db0.hares.hare", t -> t.mutator().setEnabled(false))
    .with(Column.class, "hares.db0.hares.carrot.id", c -> c.mutator().setNullable(true))
    .build();
```

**Proposed**
```java
HaresApplication app = new HaresApplicationBuilder()
    .with(Table.class, Identifier.ofTable("db0", "hares", "hare"), t -> t.mutator().setEnabled(false))
    .with(Column.class, Carrot.Identifier.ID, c -> c.mutator().setNullable(true))
    .build();
```

PROBLEM:  try to insert new row, with .newEmptyEntity() and set all required fields, leaving ones with DEFAULT 0/1/CURRENT_TIMESTAMP/whatever. However, Speedment still tries to define these fields as NULL which violates not-null constraint of course.

issues.title: Translator method forEveryTable does not execute for every table
issues.body:
The name of the `forEveryTable`, `forEverySchema` and similar methods in the `Translator.Builder` interface is misleading since the supplied code is not executed for every table under that document, only for the same or an ancestor document.

Take the following document tree:

```
projectA --+--> dbmsA
           |
           +--> dbmsB
```

If we call `forEveryDbms` on `projectA`, it will never execute. If we call `forEveryDbms` on `dbmsB`, it will execute exactly once. If we call `forEveryProject` on any of the documents, it will execute exactly once.

For the method to do what is expected, it should not only search the document ancestors for matching types but also children. In the case for calling `forEveryDbms` on `projectA`, it should execute two times, once for `dbmsA` and once for `dbmsB`.

issues.title: Potential concurrency issue when loading projects
issues.body: Since the schema loader in `2.3.0` is wrapped in a `CompletableFuture`, there is a risk that the user initiates multiple loading sessions at the same time. The `AbstractRelationalDbmsHandler` is supposed to be concurrent, but since it writes its results directly to the `ProjectComponent`, there is a risk that an cancelled loading continues processing in the background and then kicks in and overwrites the result from the real loading process. We need to make sure the CompletableFuture interface is used throughout the loading process, only writing its result once it is completely finished.

issues.title: Some settings are lost in the UI
issues.body:
When the config model is loaded from a JSON file, the tree gets updated but the underlying HashMap is not. The result of this is that the JSON file that is created when the project is saved lacks many of the fields. The problem is not apparent since the observable model is correct, it is only the underlying map that is incorrect.

**Steps to reproduce:**
1. Create a new project and open UI (works)
2. Connect to database and generate code (works)
3. Close UI and open it again so that the JSON file is loaded (here is where something happens)
4. Generate code again (the generated .json-file is wrong)

The settings are loaded into the JavaFX-components correctly, but when the map is passed to the generator, it looks like it is an old version of the map.

This issue only exists in the current `develop` branch.

issues.title: Schema names that contains dots (.) does not work
issues.body: MySQL supports schema names with a dot in them [from version 5.1.6 and up](http://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/5.1/en/identifiers.html), but Speedment can not handle them since a class name with a dot is not allowed in Java. A solution to this might be to replace dots with underscores in the generated code and escape the schema name in SQL queries.
